column4:
AES AND AU MOVE TOWARDS COOPERATION

The African Union (AU) has launched a formal rapprochement with the breakaway Alliance of Sahel States (AES), sending AU Chairperson Évariste Ndayishimiye to Burkina Faso for landmark talks with Captain Ibrahim Traoré. "I am here today in my official capacity as the President of the African Union," Ndayishimiye announced, calling for "a robust and solid bridge" linking the Sahelian states back to continental institutions.  

The AES, comprising Burkina Faso, Mali, and Niger, emerged following military takeovers prompted by a decade of extremist militants and transnational militias wreaking havoc in the three countries and the region at large. The coups led to sanctions by the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), one of the AU's building blocks. The sanctions were viewed as a neocolonial punishment, as the AES had expelled French forces and turned to new partners, framing their sovereignty as a rejection of Western tutelage.  

In an effort to preserve African cohesion and unity, Senegalese President Bassirou Diomaye Faye was designated as ECOWAS facilitator in July 2024, undertaking direct missions to Bamako and Ouagadougou and urging the revision of "extreme" sanctions. Ghana's President John Mahama has also engaged on Sahel security and is positioning for deeper dialogue with AES members.  

A successful reconciliation could stabilise a region ravaged by the war against transnational militias. Western media and NGO campaigns have aimed to discredit the AES leaders by ignoring the destabilising actors and critiquing them through a Western neoliberal lens. However, the long history of Western-backed destabilisation efforts on the continent has created a consensus among people from different parts of the continent and the diaspora that the AES's principled Pan-African mission is not merely political discourse, but that the survival of the people of the continent depends on it.   

While the visit seems like a standard diplomatic effort on behalf of the AU, its implications suggest a shift among AU countries toward valuing the AES's staunchly sovereign, anti-neocolonial policies. 

